  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1436005870" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1436005870" />
    <a title="rachel ☾" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17290119-rachel"><img alt="rachel ☾" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609395331p2/17290119.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1436005870?book_show_action=true">Nov 07, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="rachel ☾" class="user" itemprop="url" name="rachel ☾" href="/user/show/17290119-rachel">rachel ☾</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17290119-rachel?shelf=3-star">3-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17290119-rachel?shelf=young-adult-lit">young-adult-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17290119-rachel?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1436005870" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13502087312785200261"><b>3.5 stars</b><br/><br/><blockquote>
  <i>It be better, I think, to climb out in search of something, instead of hating, what you&apos;re leaving. </i>
</blockquote><br/><br/>There are some books that don’t need to be fancy, that don’t need action or drama or ridiculous love triangles to get your attention. <i>Son</i> is one of those rare books that is quiet, but impacting. Its writing style could easily be described as simple, even plain, but I don’t think that quite covers it. There’s something alluring about Lowry’s style, something almost gravitational, which</span>
  <span id="freeText13502087312785200261" style="display:none"><b>3.5 stars</b><br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>It be better, I think, to climb out in search of something, instead of hating, what you're leaving. </i>
</blockquote><br /><br />There are some books that don’t need to be fancy, that don’t need action or drama or ridiculous love triangles to get your attention. <i>Son</i> is one of those rare books that is quiet, but impacting. Its writing style could easily be described as simple, even plain, but I don’t think that quite covers it. There’s something alluring about Lowry’s style, something almost gravitational, which pulls you in and manages to quietly spin this tale of love, loss and hope in the bleakest of circumstances that will tug at your heartstrings and leave you questioning everything you thought about human spirit. It happens before you realise that you’ve speed through the entire 400-paged book, even before you realise that you’re quietly crying into the pages.<br /><br />While, I’m not going to pretend this is my favourite Lois Lowry book to date, or even my favourite <i>Giver Quartet</i> installment (that would have to be <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12930.Messenger__The_Giver___3_" title="Messenger (The Giver, #3) by Lois Lowry" rel="nofollow noopener">Messenger</a>), I would have to say that this was exactly what the series it needed. It tied up everything from the last three books in a pretty, little bow. Although I wouldn’t be distraught if a fifth book was written, I don’t think I’d be begging for it anytime soon. I’m happy with the direction the story took, where the characters ended up <br /><br /><br />Starting the story way back in the beginning, even before the events of <i>The Giver</i>, was perfect. We needed to see and learn about Claire’s role in the Community, and how her part in Jonas’ shenanigans unfolded. Her relationship with Gabe and Jonas’ father made me smile. And the Community, while horrible, always fascinates me. I honestly believe that our society could one day end up like that, and that’s why it scares me so much. It’s so eye-opening looking into a society so rigid, so deluded. It reminds me of everything I have, and why I am so passionate about fighting for equality and freedom.<br /><br />The second part, however, was sadly dull, even – dare I say it – a tad boring. I understand that it was important to the story, and I appreciated that Claire had to overcome obstacles to find her son, she didn’t just magically find him and get her happily ever after. But reading about her daily life in a little fishing village wasn’t exactly riveting, but still somewhat climatic with the climb scene. <br /><br />What made up for it was the ending. I wish it could have been longer, but I loved the involvement of the Trademaster, Gabe and Jonas. We needed to see what happened to our previous protagonists and it was heart-warming to see Kira with their happy little family. The ending reminded me of A Monster Calls, but it was surprising – in the best possible way – and a kind of haunting beautiful. And we got a little HEA – yeah! <br /><br />Overall, I’ve really enjoyed reading this series and will be sad to see it over with. I thought Claire’s story was important and the perfect way to wrap the four stories together. The first and third parts were well-done, but the second part was too long and rather dull. It dragged the story down, and I wished that it had been cut down to the bare essentials. It felt unnecessary. The ending was surprising, but I loved it. I definitely want to read more of this author’s books in the future.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13502087312785200261" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


